					<description><![CDATA[<p>Artemis secured $70 million in combined seed and Series A funding to help improve the advancement of autonomous AI agents that would take centre stage as upgrades to outdated, rule-based</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/artemis-raises-70m-for-ai-cybersecurity-platform-growth/" data-wpel-link="internal">Artemis Raises $70M for AI Cybersecurity Platform Growth</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.artemis-security.it/en/artemis-cybersecurity-tool/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Artemis </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">secured $70 million in combined seed and Series A </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/expo-secures-45m-and-unveils-new-expo-agent-tool/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">to help </span><span style="font-weight: 400">improve the advancement of autonomous AI agents that would take centre stage as upgrades to outdated, rule-based defence systems that involve fighting machine-speed attacks.</span><span style="font-weight: 400"> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The funding also saw the participation of a number of remarkable investors, including 1st Round Capital, Brightmind and others, along with Felicis as the lead investor and a couple of other industry veterans as the co-investors. Also investing were strategic backers of the startup from Demisto, as well as Abnormal AI and former professionals of Splunk, CrowdStrike, Microsoft, and Palo Alto Networks.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The End of the &#8220;Human-Speed&#8221; Era</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The launch of Artemis comes at a critical juncture for enterprise security. As generative AI becomes a staple tool for cybercriminals, the velocity and sophistication of attacks have outpaced the ability of human analysts to respond. Traditional Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) systems rely on static rules, logic that can take weeks for a human to write but mere seconds for an AI-driven threat to bypass.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200129" style="width: 413px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200129" class="wp-image-200129" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Artemis.jpeg" alt="Artemis logo" width="403" height="403" /><p id="caption-attachment-200129" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Artemis</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Legacy detection was built for a world where humans attacked humans,&#8221; said Shachar Hirshberg, co-founder and CEO of Artemis and former lead of AWS’s GuardDuty. Today, AI-driven attacks never execute the same way twice. They adapt in real-time, often finishing their mission before a human defender even receives an alert. We built Artemis to give defenders that same speed and adaptability.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News:</span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/expo-secures-45m-and-unveils-new-expo-agent-tool/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400"> Expo Secures $45M and Unveils New Expo Agent Tool</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">An &#8220;AI Brain&#8221; for the Enterprise</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">At the heart of the Artemis platform is a proprietary dynamic data model that functions as a centralised &#8220;cybersecurity brain&#8221;. Unlike traditional tools that create &#8220;noise&#8221; by flooding dashboards with disconnected alerts, Artemis’s platform uses autonomous AI agents to correlate telemetry data across a company’s entire environment, spanning cloud workloads, identity systems, endpoints, and first-party applications.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By fusing this behavioural data with specific business context, the platform understands what &#8220;normal&#8221; looks like for a specific organisation. When a threat is detected, the AI agents don&#8217;t just alert a human; they autonomously investigate the signal, reconstruct the entire attack story, and can even execute remediation actions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Dan Shiebler, co-founder and CTO and former head of machine learning at Abnormal AI, emphasised that the breakthrough isn&#8217;t just &#8220;better AI&#8221; but deeper context. The real shift is giving models a structured understanding of how an organisation functions. This allows for reliable detection and automated response that previously required weeks of manual correlation,&#8221; Shiebler noted.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Rapid Growth and Market Disruption</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Artemis&#8217;s rise has been meteoric. Founded only six months ago, the company has already deployed its platform in production for several Fortune 500 companies and leaders in the banking and technology sectors. Reports indicate the platform is already processing billions of events per hour, successfully identifying threats that bypassed traditional legacy stacks.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The $70 million infusion will be used to aggressively scale Artemis’s engineering and research teams, particularly in New York and Israel. The company also plans to expand its go-to-market strategy as enterprises look to consolidate their fragmented security tools into more cohesive, AI-driven platforms.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Many industry observers believe the size of the Series A round, given the company&#8217;s youth, is an unequivocal endorsement of the “AI vs. AI” thesis. Investors are betting that the future of cybersecurity belongs not to the company with the most rules, but to the system that can think and act the fastest.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
